<H1>Debian Policy Manual <BR>Chapter 5 - Control files and their fields =
</H1>
<P>The package management system manipulates data represented in a =
common=20
format, known as <EM>control data</EM>, stored in <EM>control =
files</EM>.=20
Control files are used for source packages, binary packages and the=20
<CODE>.changes</CODE> files which control the installation of uploaded =
files[<A=20
href=3D"http://www.debian.org/doc/debian-policy/footnotes.html#f31"=20
name=3Dfr31>31</A>]. </P>
<HR>

<H2><A name=3Ds-controlsyntax></A>5.1 Syntax of control files</H2>
<P>A control file consists of one or more paragraphs of fields[<A=20
href=3D"http://www.debian.org/doc/debian-policy/footnotes.html#f32"=20
name=3Dfr32>32</A>]. The paragraphs are separated by empty lines. =
Parsers may=20
accept lines consisting solely of spaces and tabs as paragraph =
separators, but=20
control files should use empty lines. Some control files allow only one=20
paragraph; others allow several, in which case each paragraph usually =
refers to=20
a different package. (For example, in source packages, the first =
paragraph=20
refers to the source package, and later paragraphs refer to binary =
packages=20
generated from the source.) The ordering of the paragraphs in control =
files is=20
significant. </P>
<P>Each paragraph consists of a series of data fields. Each field =
consists of=20
the field name followed by a colon and then the data/value associated =
with that=20
field. The field name is composed of US-ASCII characters excluding =
control=20
characters, space, and colon (i.e., characters in the ranges 33-57 and =
59-126,=20
inclusive). Field names must not begin with the comment character,=20
<SAMP>#</SAMP>. </P>
<P>The field ends at the end of the line or at the end of the last =
continuation=20
line (see below). Horizontal whitespace (spaces and tabs) may occur =
immediately=20
before or after the value and is ignored there; it is conventional to =
put a=20
single space after the colon. For example, a field might be: </P><PRE>   =
  Package: libc6
</PRE>
<P>the field name is <SAMP>Package</SAMP> and the field value=20
<SAMP>libc6</SAMP>. </P>
<P>A paragraph must not contain more than one instance of a particular =
field=20
name. </P>
<P>There are three types of fields: </P>
<DL>
  <DT>simple</DT>
  <DD>
  <P>The field, including its value, must be a single line. Folding of =
the field=20
  is not permitted. This is the default field type if the definition of =
the=20
  field does not specify a different type. </P></DD></DL>
<DL>
  <DT>folded</DT>
  <DD>
  <P>The value of a folded field is a logical line that may span several =
lines.=20
  The lines after the first are called continuation lines and must start =
with a=20
  space or a tab. Whitespace, including any newlines, is not significant =
in the=20
  field values of folded fields.[<A=20
  href=3D"http://www.debian.org/doc/debian-policy/footnotes.html#f33"=20
  name=3Dfr33>33</A>] </P></DD></DL>
<DL>
  <DT>multiline</DT>
  <DD>
  <P>The value of a multiline field may comprise multiple continuation =
lines.=20
  The first line of the value, the part on the same line as the field =
name,=20
  often has special significance or may have to be empty. Other lines =
are added=20
  following the same syntax as the continuation lines of the folded =
fields.=20
  Whitespace, including newlines, is significant in the values of =
multiline=20
  fields. </P></DD></DL>
<P>Whitespace must not appear inside names (of packages, architectures, =
files or=20
anything else) or version numbers, or between the characters of =
multi-character=20
version relationships. </P>
<P>The presence and purpose of a field, and the syntax of its value may =
differ=20
between types of control files. </P>
<P>Field names are not case-sensitive, but it is usual to capitalize the =
field=20
names using mixed case as shown below. Field values are case-sensitive =
unless=20
the description of the field says otherwise. </P>
<P>Paragraph separators (empty lines) and lines consisting only of =
spaces and=20
tabs are not allowed within field values or between fields. Empty lines =
in field=20
values are usually escaped by representing them by a space followed by a =
dot.=20
</P>
<P>Lines starting with # without any preceding whitespace are comments =
lines=20
that are only permitted in source package control files=20
(<CODE>debian/control</CODE>). These comment lines are ignored, even =
between two=20
continuation lines. They do not end logical lines. </P>
<P>All control files must be encoded in UTF-8. </P>
<HR>

