<H2><A name=3Ds-controlfieldslist></A>5.6 List of fields</H2>
<HR>

<H3><A name=3Ds-f-Source></A>5.6.1 <SAMP>Source</SAMP></H3>
<P>This field identifies the source package name. </P>
<P>In <CODE>debian/control</CODE> or a <CODE>.dsc</CODE> file, this =
field must=20
contain only the name of the source package. </P>
<P>In a binary package control file or a <CODE>.changes</CODE> file, the =
source=20
package name may be followed by a version number in parentheses[<A=20
href=3D"http://www.debian.org/doc/debian-policy/footnotes.html#f34"=20
name=3Dfr34>34</A>]. This version number may be omitted (and is, by=20
<CODE>dpkg-gencontrol</CODE>) if it has the same value as the=20
<SAMP>Version</SAMP> field of the binary package in question. The field =
itself=20
may be omitted from a binary package control file when the source =
package has=20
the same name and version as the binary package. </P>
<P>Package names (both source and binary, see <A=20
href=3D"http://www.debian.org/doc/debian-policy/ch-controlfields.html#s-f=
-Package"><SAMP>Package</SAMP>,=20
Section 5.6.7</A>) must consist only of lower case letters =
(<SAMP>a-z</SAMP>),=20
digits (<SAMP>0-9</SAMP>), plus (<SAMP>+</SAMP>) and minus =
(<SAMP>-</SAMP>)=20
signs, and periods (<SAMP>.</SAMP>). They must be at least two =
characters long=20
and must start with an alphanumeric character. </P>
<HR>

<H3><A name=3Ds-f-Maintainer></A>5.6.2 <SAMP>Maintainer</SAMP></H3>
<P>The package maintainer's name and email address. The name must come =
first,=20
then the email address inside angle brackets <SAMP>&lt;&gt;</SAMP> (in =
RFC822=20
format). </P>
<P>If the maintainer's name contains a full stop then the whole field =
will not=20
work directly as an email address due to a misfeature in the syntax =
specified in=20
RFC822; a program using this field as an address must check for this and =
correct=20
the problem if necessary (for example by putting the name in round =
brackets and=20
moving it to the end, and bringing the email address forward). </P>
<P>See <A=20
href=3D"http://www.debian.org/doc/debian-policy/ch-binary.html#s-maintain=
er">The=20
maintainer of a package, Section 3.3</A> for additional requirements and =

information about package maintainers. </P>
<HR>

<H3><A name=3Ds-f-Uploaders></A>5.6.3 <SAMP>Uploaders</SAMP></H3>
<P>List of the names and email addresses of co-maintainers of the =
package, if=20
any. If the package has other maintainers besides the one named in the =
<A=20
href=3D"http://www.debian.org/doc/debian-policy/ch-controlfields.html#s-f=
-Maintainer">Maintainer=20
field</A>, their names and email addresses should be listed here. The =
format of=20
each entry is the same as that of the Maintainer field, and multiple =
entries=20
must be comma separated. </P>
<P>This is normally an optional field, but if the =
<SAMP>Maintainer</SAMP>=20
control field names a group of people and a shared email address, the=20
<SAMP>Uploaders</SAMP> field must be present and must contain at least =
one human=20
with their personal email address. </P>
<P>The Uploaders field in <CODE>debian/control</CODE> can be folded. =
</P>
<HR>

<H3><A name=3Ds-f-Changed-By></A>5.6.4 <SAMP>Changed-By</SAMP></H3>
<P>The name and email address of the person who prepared this version of =
the=20
package, usually a maintainer. The syntax is the same as for the <A=20
href=3D"http://www.debian.org/doc/debian-policy/ch-controlfields.html#s-f=
-Maintainer">Maintainer=20
field</A>. </P>
<HR>

<H3><A name=3Ds-f-Section></A>5.6.5 <SAMP>Section</SAMP></H3>
<P>This field specifies an application area into which the package has =
been=20
classified. See <A=20
href=3D"http://www.debian.org/doc/debian-policy/ch-archive.html#s-subsect=
ions">Sections,=20
Section 2.4</A>. </P>
<P>When it appears in the <CODE>debian/control</CODE> file, it gives the =
value=20
for the subfield of the same name in the <SAMP>Files</SAMP> field of the =

<CODE>.changes</CODE> file. It also gives the default for the same field =
in the=20
binary packages. </P>
<HR>

<H3><A name=3Ds-f-Priority></A>5.6.6 <SAMP>Priority</SAMP></H3>
<P>This field represents how important it is that the user have the =
package=20
installed. See <A=20
href=3D"http://www.debian.org/doc/debian-policy/ch-archive.html#s-priorit=
ies">Priorities,=20
Section 2.5</A>. </P>
<P>When it appears in the <CODE>debian/control</CODE> file, it gives the =
value=20
for the subfield of the same name in the <SAMP>Files</SAMP> field of the =

<CODE>.changes</CODE> file. It also gives the default for the same field =
in the=20
binary packages. </P>
<HR>

<H3><A name=3Ds-f-Package></A>5.6.7 <SAMP>Package</SAMP></H3>
<P>The name of the binary package. </P>
<P>Binary package names must follow the same syntax and restrictions as =
source=20
package names. See <A=20
href=3D"http://www.debian.org/doc/debian-policy/ch-controlfields.html#s-f=
-Source"><SAMP>Source</SAMP>,=20
Section 5.6.1</A> for the details. </P>
<HR>

<H3><A name=3Ds-f-Architecture></A>5.6.8 <SAMP>Architecture</SAMP></H3>
<P>Depending on context and the control file used, the =
<SAMP>Architecture</SAMP>=20
field can include the following sets of values: </P>
<UL>
  <LI>
  <P>A unique single word identifying a Debian machine architecture as =
described=20
  in <A=20
  =
href=3D"http://www.debian.org/doc/debian-policy/ch-customized-programs.ht=
ml#s-arch-spec">Architecture=20
  specification strings, Section 11.1</A>. </P></LI></UL>
<UL>
  <LI>
  <P>An architecture wildcard identifying a set of Debian machine =
architectures,=20
  see <A=20
  =
href=3D"http://www.debian.org/doc/debian-policy/ch-customized-programs.ht=
ml#s-arch-wildcard-spec">Architecture=20
  wildcards, Section 11.1.1</A>. <SAMP>any</SAMP> matches all Debian =
machine=20
  architectures and is the most frequently used. </P></LI></UL>
<UL>
  <LI>
  <P><SAMP>all</SAMP>, which indicates an architecture-independent =
package.=20
  </P></LI></UL>
<UL>
  <LI>
  <P><SAMP>source</SAMP>, which indicates a source package. =
</P></LI></UL>
<P>In the main <CODE>debian/control</CODE> file in the source package, =
this=20
field may contain the special value <SAMP>all</SAMP>, the special =
architecture=20
wildcard <SAMP>any</SAMP>, or a list of specific and wildcard =
architectures=20
separated by spaces. If <SAMP>all</SAMP> or <SAMP>any</SAMP> appears, =
that value=20
must be the entire contents of the field. Most packages will use either=20
<SAMP>all</SAMP> or <SAMP>any</SAMP>. </P>
<P>Specifying a specific list of architectures indicates that the source =
will=20
build an architecture-dependent package only on architectures included =
in the=20
list. Specifying a list of architecture wildcards indicates that the =
source will=20
build an architecture-dependent package on only those architectures that =
match=20
any of the specified architecture wildcards. Specifying a list of =
architectures=20
or architecture wildcards other than <SAMP>any</SAMP> is for the =
minority of=20
cases where a program is not portable or is not useful on some =
architectures.=20
Where possible, the program should be made portable instead. </P>
<P>In the Debian source control file <CODE>.dsc</CODE>, this field =
contains a=20
list of architectures and architecture wildcards separated by spaces. =
When the=20
list contains the architecture wildcard <SAMP>any</SAMP>, the only other =
value=20
allowed in the list is <SAMP>all</SAMP>. </P>
<P>The list may include (or consist solely of) the special value=20
<SAMP>all</SAMP>. In other words, in <CODE>.dsc</CODE> files unlike the=20
<CODE>debian/control</CODE>, <SAMP>all</SAMP> may occur in combination =
with=20
specific architectures. The <SAMP>Architecture</SAMP> field in the =
Debian source=20
control file <CODE>.dsc</CODE> is generally constructed from the=20
<SAMP>Architecture</SAMP> fields in the <CODE>debian/control</CODE> in =
the=20
source package. </P>
<P>Specifying only <SAMP>any</SAMP> indicates that the source package =
isn't=20
dependent on any particular architecture and should compile fine on any =
one. The=20
produced binary package(s) will be specific to whatever the current =
build=20
architecture is. </P>
<P>Specifying only <SAMP>all</SAMP> indicates that the source package =
will only=20
build architecture-independent packages. </P>
<P>Specifying <SAMP>any all</SAMP> indicates that the source package =
isn't=20
dependent on any particular architecture. The set of produced binary =
packages=20
will include at least one architecture-dependant package and one=20
architecture-independent package. </P>
<P>Specifying a list of architectures or architecture wildcards =
indicates that=20
the source will build an architecture-dependent package, and will only =
work=20
correctly on the listed or matching architectures. If the source package =
also=20
builds at least one architecture-independent package, <SAMP>all</SAMP> =
will also=20
be included in the list. </P>
<P>In a <CODE>.changes</CODE> file, the <SAMP>Architecture</SAMP> field =
lists=20
the architecture(s) of the package(s) currently being uploaded. This =
will be a=20
list; if the source for the package is also being uploaded, the special =
entry=20
<SAMP>source</SAMP> is also present. <SAMP>all</SAMP> will be present if =
any=20
architecture-independent packages are being uploaded. Architecture =
wildcards=20
such as <SAMP>any</SAMP> must never occur in the =
<SAMP>Architecture</SAMP> field=20
in the <CODE>.changes</CODE> file. </P>
<P>See <A=20
href=3D"http://www.debian.org/doc/debian-policy/ch-source.html#s-debianru=
les">Main=20
building script: <CODE>debian/rules</CODE>, Section 4.9</A> for =
information on=20
how to get the architecture for the build process. </P>
<HR>

<H3><A name=3Ds-f-Essential></A>5.6.9 <SAMP>Essential</SAMP></H3>
<P>This is a boolean field which may occur only in the control file of a =
binary=20
package or in a per-package fields paragraph of a source package control =
file.=20
</P>
<P>If set to <SAMP>yes</SAMP> then the package management system will =
refuse to=20
remove the package (upgrading and replacing it is still possible). The =
other=20
possible value is <SAMP>no</SAMP>, which is the same as not having the =
field at=20
all. </P>
<HR>

<H3><A name=3Ds5.6.10></A>5.6.10 Package interrelationship fields:=20
<SAMP>Depends</SAMP>, <SAMP>Pre-Depends</SAMP>, <SAMP>Recommends</SAMP>, =

<SAMP>Suggests</SAMP>, <SAMP>Breaks</SAMP>, <SAMP>Conflicts</SAMP>,=20
<SAMP>Provides</SAMP>, <SAMP>Replaces</SAMP>, <SAMP>Enhances</SAMP></H3>
<P>These fields describe the package's relationships with other =
packages. Their=20
syntax and semantics are described in <A=20
href=3D"http://www.debian.org/doc/debian-policy/ch-relationships.html">De=
claring=20
relationships between packages, Chapter 7</A>. </P>
<HR>

<H3><A name=3Ds-f-Standards-Version></A>5.6.11 =
<SAMP>Standards-Version</SAMP></H3>
<P>The most recent version of the standards (the policy manual and =
associated=20
texts) with which the package complies. </P>
<P>The version number has four components: major and minor version =
number and=20
major and minor patch level. When the standards change in a way that =
requires=20
every package to change the major number will be changed. Significant =
changes=20
that will require work in many packages will be signaled by a change to =
the=20
minor number. The major patch level will be changed for any change to =
the=20
meaning of the standards, however small; the minor patch level will be =
changed=20
when only cosmetic, typographical or other edits are made which neither =
change=20
the meaning of the document nor affect the contents of packages. </P>
<P>Thus only the first three components of the policy version are =
significant in=20
the <EM>Standards-Version</EM> control field, and so either these three=20
components or all four components may be specified.[<A=20
href=3D"http://www.debian.org/doc/debian-policy/footnotes.html#f35"=20
name=3Dfr35>35</A>] </P>
<HR>

<H3><A name=3Ds-f-Version></A>5.6.12 <SAMP>Version</SAMP></H3>
<P>The version number of a package. The format is:=20
[<VAR>epoch</VAR><SAMP>:</SAMP>]<VAR>upstream_version</VAR>[<SAMP>-</SAMP=
><VAR>debian_revision</VAR>]=20
</P>
<P>The three components here are: </P>
<DL>
  <DT><VAR>epoch</VAR></DT>
  <DD>
  <P>This is a single (generally small) unsigned integer. It may be =
omitted, in=20
  which case zero is assumed. If it is omitted then the=20
  <VAR>upstream_version</VAR> may not contain any colons. </P>
  <P>It is provided to allow mistakes in the version numbers of older =
versions=20
  of a package, and also a package's previous version numbering schemes, =
to be=20
  left behind. </P></DD></DL>
<DL>
  <DT><VAR>upstream_version</VAR></DT>
  <DD>
  <P>This is the main part of the version number. It is usually the =
version=20
  number of the original ("upstream") package from which the =
<CODE>.deb</CODE>=20
  file has been made, if this is applicable. Usually this will be in the =
same=20
  format as that specified by the upstream author(s); however, it may =
need to be=20
  reformatted to fit into the package management system's format and =
comparison=20
  scheme. </P>
  <P>The comparison behavior of the package management system with =
respect to=20
  the <VAR>upstream_version</VAR> is described below. The=20
  <VAR>upstream_version</VAR> portion of the version number is =
mandatory. </P>
  <P>The <VAR>upstream_version</VAR> may contain only alphanumerics[<A=20
  href=3D"http://www.debian.org/doc/debian-policy/footnotes.html#f36"=20
  name=3Dfr36>36</A>] and the characters <SAMP>.</SAMP> <SAMP>+</SAMP>=20
  <SAMP>-</SAMP> <SAMP>:</SAMP> <SAMP>~</SAMP> (full stop, plus, hyphen, =
colon,=20
  tilde) and should start with a digit. If there is no=20
  <VAR>debian_revision</VAR> then hyphens are not allowed; if there is =
no=20
  <VAR>epoch</VAR> then colons are not allowed. </P></DD></DL>
<DL>
  <DT><VAR>debian_revision</VAR></DT>
  <DD>
  <P>This part of the version number specifies the version of the Debian =
package=20
  based on the upstream version. It may contain only alphanumerics and =
the=20
  characters <SAMP>+</SAMP> <SAMP>.</SAMP> <SAMP>~</SAMP> (plus, full =
stop,=20
  tilde) and is compared in the same way as the =
<VAR>upstream_version</VAR> is.=20
  </P>
  <P>It is optional; if it isn't present then the =
<VAR>upstream_version</VAR>=20
  may not contain a hyphen. This format represents the case where a =
piece of=20
  software was written specifically to be a Debian package, where the =
Debian=20
  package source must always be identical to the pristine source and =
therefore=20
  no revision indication is required. </P>
  <P>It is conventional to restart the <VAR>debian_revision</VAR> at=20
  <SAMP>1</SAMP> each time the <VAR>upstream_version</VAR> is increased. =
</P>
  <P>The package management system will break the version number apart =
at the=20
  last hyphen in the string (if there is one) to determine the=20
  <VAR>upstream_version</VAR> and <VAR>debian_revision</VAR>. The =
absence of a=20
  <VAR>debian_revision</VAR> is equivalent to a =
<VAR>debian_revision</VAR> of=20
  <SAMP>0</SAMP>. </P></DD></DL>
<P>When comparing two version numbers, first the <VAR>epoch</VAR> of =
each are=20
compared, then the <VAR>upstream_version</VAR> if <VAR>epoch</VAR> is =
equal, and=20
then <VAR>debian_revision</VAR> if <VAR>upstream_version</VAR> is also =
equal.=20
<VAR>epoch</VAR> is compared numerically. The =
<VAR>upstream_version</VAR> and=20
<VAR>debian_revision</VAR> parts are compared by the package management =
system=20
using the following algorithm: </P>
<P>The strings are compared from left to right. </P>
<P>First the initial part of each string consisting entirely of =
non-digit=20
characters is determined. These two parts (one of which may be empty) =
are=20
compared lexically. If a difference is found it is returned. The lexical =

comparison is a comparison of ASCII values modified so that all the =
letters sort=20
earlier than all the non-letters and so that a tilde sorts before =
anything, even=20
the end of a part. For example, the following parts are in sorted order =
from=20
earliest to latest: <SAMP>~~</SAMP>, <SAMP>~~a</SAMP>, <SAMP>~</SAMP>, =
the empty=20
part, <SAMP>a</SAMP>.[<A=20
href=3D"http://www.debian.org/doc/debian-policy/footnotes.html#f37"=20
name=3Dfr37>37</A>] </P>
<P>Then the initial part of the remainder of each string which consists =
entirely=20
of digit characters is determined. The numerical values of these two =
parts are=20
compared, and any difference found is returned as the result of the =
comparison.=20
For these purposes an empty string (which can only occur at the end of =
one or=20
both version strings being compared) counts as zero. </P>
<P>These two steps (comparing and removing initial non-digit strings and =
initial=20
digit strings) are repeated until a difference is found or both strings =
are=20
exhausted. </P>
<P>Note that the purpose of epochs is to allow us to leave behind =
mistakes in=20
version numbering, and to cope with situations where the version =
numbering=20
scheme changes. It is <EM>not</EM> intended to cope with version numbers =

containing strings of letters which the package management system cannot =

interpret (such as <SAMP>ALPHA</SAMP> or <SAMP>pre-</SAMP>), or with =
silly=20
orderings.[<A =
href=3D"http://www.debian.org/doc/debian-policy/footnotes.html#f38"=20
name=3Dfr38>38</A>] </P>
<HR>

<H3><A name=3Ds-f-Description></A>5.6.13 <SAMP>Description</SAMP></H3>
<P>In a source or binary control file, the <SAMP>Description</SAMP> =
field=20
contains a description of the binary package, consisting of two parts, =
the=20
synopsis or the short description, and the long description. It is a =
multiline=20
field with the following format: </P><PRE>     	Description: &lt;single =
line synopsis&gt;
     	 &lt;extended description over several lines&gt;
</PRE>
<P>The lines in the extended description can have these formats: </P>
<UL>
  <LI>
  <P>Those starting with a single space are part of a paragraph. =
Successive=20
  lines of this form will be word-wrapped when displayed. The leading =
space will=20
  usually be stripped off. The line must contain at least one =
non-whitespace=20
  character. </P></LI></UL>
<UL>
  <LI>
  <P>Those starting with two or more spaces. These will be displayed =
verbatim.=20
  If the display cannot be panned horizontally, the displaying program =
will line=20
  wrap them "hard" (i.e., without taking account of word breaks). If it =
can they=20
  will be allowed to trail off to the right. None, one or two initial =
spaces may=20
  be deleted, but the number of spaces deleted from each line will be =
the same=20
  (so that you can have indenting work correctly, for example). The line =
must=20
  contain at least one non-whitespace character. </P></LI></UL>
<UL>
  <LI>
  <P>Those containing a single space followed by a single full stop =
character.=20
  These are rendered as blank lines. This is the <EM>only</EM> way to =
get a=20
  blank line[<A=20
  href=3D"http://www.debian.org/doc/debian-policy/footnotes.html#f39"=20
  name=3Dfr39>39</A>]. </P></LI></UL>
<UL>
  <LI>
  <P>Those containing a space, a full stop and some more characters. =
These are=20
  for future expansion. Do not use them. </P></LI></UL>
<P>Do not use tab characters. Their effect is not predictable. </P>
<P>See <A=20
href=3D"http://www.debian.org/doc/debian-policy/ch-binary.html#s-descript=
ions">The=20
description of a package, Section 3.4</A> for further information on =
this. </P>
<P>In a <CODE>.changes</CODE> file, the <SAMP>Description</SAMP> field =
contains=20
a summary of the descriptions for the packages being uploaded. For this =
case,=20
the first line of the field value (the part on the same line as=20
<SAMP>Description:</SAMP>) is always empty. It is a multiline field, =
with one=20
line per package. Each line is indented by one space and contains the =
name of a=20
binary package, a space, a hyphen (<SAMP>-</SAMP>), a space, and the =
short=20
description line from that package. </P>
<HR>

<H3><A name=3Ds-f-Distribution></A>5.6.14 <SAMP>Distribution</SAMP></H3>
<P>In a <CODE>.changes</CODE> file or parsed changelog output this =
contains the=20
(space-separated) name(s) of the distribution(s) where this version of =
the=20
package should be installed. Valid distributions are determined by the =
archive=20
maintainers.[<A=20
href=3D"http://www.debian.org/doc/debian-policy/footnotes.html#f40"=20
name=3Dfr40>40</A>] The Debian archive software only supports listing a =
single=20
distribution. Migration of packages to other distributions is handled =
outside of=20
the upload process. </P>
<HR>

<H3><A name=3Ds-f-Date></A>5.6.15 <SAMP>Date</SAMP></H3>
<P>This field includes the date the package was built or last edited. It =
must be=20
in the same format as the <VAR>date</VAR> in a =
<CODE>debian/changelog</CODE>=20
entry. </P>
<P>The value of this field is usually extracted from the=20
<CODE>debian/changelog</CODE> file - see <A=20
href=3D"http://www.debian.org/doc/debian-policy/ch-source.html#s-dpkgchan=
gelog">Debian=20
changelog: <CODE>debian/changelog</CODE>, Section 4.4</A>). </P>
<HR>

<H3><A name=3Ds-f-Format></A>5.6.16 <SAMP>Format</SAMP></H3>
<P>In <A=20
href=3D"http://www.debian.org/doc/debian-policy/ch-controlfields.html#s-d=
ebianchangesfiles"><CODE>.changes</CODE></A>=20
files, this field declares the format version of that file. The syntax =
of the=20
field value is the same as that of a <A=20
href=3D"http://www.debian.org/doc/debian-policy/ch-controlfields.html#s-f=
-Version">package=20
version number</A> except that no epoch or Debian revision is allowed. =
The=20
format described in this document is <SAMP>1.8</SAMP>. </P>
<P>In <A=20
href=3D"http://www.debian.org/doc/debian-policy/ch-controlfields.html#s-d=
ebiansourcecontrolfiles"><CODE>.dsc</CODE>=20
Debian source control</A> files, this field declares the format of the =
source=20
package. The field value is used by programs acting on a source package =
to=20
interpret the list of files in the source package and determine how to =
unpack=20
it. The syntax of the field value is a numeric major revision, a period, =
a=20
numeric minor revision, and then an optional subtype after whitespace, =
which if=20
specified is an alphanumeric word in parentheses. The subtype is =
optional in the=20
syntax but may be mandatory for particular source format revisions. [<A=20
href=3D"http://www.debian.org/doc/debian-policy/footnotes.html#f41"=20
name=3Dfr41>41</A>] </P>
<HR>

<H3><A name=3Ds-f-Urgency></A>5.6.17 <SAMP>Urgency</SAMP></H3>
<P>This is a description of how important it is to upgrade to this =
version from=20
previous ones. It consists of a single keyword taking one of the values=20
<SAMP>low</SAMP>, <SAMP>medium</SAMP>, <SAMP>high</SAMP>,=20
<SAMP>emergency</SAMP>, or <SAMP>critical</SAMP>[<A=20
href=3D"http://www.debian.org/doc/debian-policy/footnotes.html#f42"=20
name=3Dfr42>42</A>] (not case-sensitive) followed by an optional =
commentary=20
(separated by a space) which is usually in parentheses. For example: =
</P><PRE>       Urgency: low (HIGH for users of diversions)
</PRE>
<P>The value of this field is usually extracted from the=20
<CODE>debian/changelog</CODE> file - see <A=20
href=3D"http://www.debian.org/doc/debian-policy/ch-source.html#s-dpkgchan=
gelog">Debian=20
changelog: <CODE>debian/changelog</CODE>, Section 4.4</A>. </P>
<HR>

<H3><A name=3Ds-f-Changes></A>5.6.18 <SAMP>Changes</SAMP></H3>
<P>This multiline field contains the human-readable changes data, =
describing the=20
differences between the last version and the current one. </P>
<P>The first line of the field value (the part on the same line as=20
<SAMP>Changes:</SAMP>) is always empty. The content of the field is =
expressed as=20
continuation lines, with each line indented by at least one space. Blank =
lines=20
must be represented by a line consisting only of a space and a full stop =

(<SAMP>.</SAMP>). </P>
<P>The value of this field is usually extracted from the=20
<CODE>debian/changelog</CODE> file - see <A=20
href=3D"http://www.debian.org/doc/debian-policy/ch-source.html#s-dpkgchan=
gelog">Debian=20
changelog: <CODE>debian/changelog</CODE>, Section 4.4</A>). </P>
<P>Each version's change information should be preceded by a "title" =
line giving=20
at least the version, distribution(s) and urgency, in a human-readable =
way. </P>
<P>If data from several versions is being returned the entry for the =
most recent=20
version should be returned first, and entries should be separated by the =

representation of a blank line (the "title" line may also be followed by =
the=20
representation of a blank line). </P>
<HR>

<H3><A name=3Ds-f-Binary></A>5.6.19 <SAMP>Binary</SAMP></H3>
<P>This folded field is a list of binary packages. Its syntax and =
meaning varies=20
depending on the control file in which it appears. </P>
<P>When it appears in the <CODE>.dsc</CODE> file, it lists binary =
packages which=20
a source package can produce, separated by commas[<A=20
href=3D"http://www.debian.org/doc/debian-policy/footnotes.html#f43"=20
name=3Dfr43>43</A>]. The source package does not necessarily produce all =
of these=20
binary packages for every architecture. The source control file doesn't =
contain=20
details of which architectures are appropriate for which of the binary =
packages.=20
</P>
<P>When it appears in a <CODE>.changes</CODE> file, it lists the names =
of the=20
binary packages being uploaded, separated by whitespace (not commas). =
</P>
<HR>

<H3><A name=3Ds-f-Installed-Size></A>5.6.20 =
<SAMP>Installed-Size</SAMP></H3>
<P>This field appears in the control files of binary packages, and in =
the=20
<CODE>Packages</CODE> files. It gives an estimate of the total amount of =
disk=20
space required to install the named package. Actual installed size may =
vary=20
based on block size, file system properties, or actions taken by package =

maintainer scripts. </P>
<P>The disk space is given as the integer value of the estimated =
installed size=20
in bytes, divided by 1024 and rounded up. </P>
<HR>

<H3><A name=3Ds-f-Files></A>5.6.21 <SAMP>Files</SAMP></H3>
<P>This field contains a list of files with information about each one. =
The=20
exact information and syntax varies with the context. </P>
<P>In all cases, Files is a multiline field. The first line of the field =
value=20
(the part on the same line as <SAMP>Files:</SAMP>) is always empty. The =
content=20
of the field is expressed as continuation lines, one line per file. Each =
line=20
must be indented by one space and contain a number of sub-fields, =
separated by=20
spaces, as described below. </P>
<P>In the <CODE>.dsc</CODE> file, each line contains the MD5 checksum, =
size and=20
filename of the tar file and (if applicable) diff file which make up the =

remainder of the source package[<A=20
href=3D"http://www.debian.org/doc/debian-policy/footnotes.html#f44"=20
name=3Dfr44>44</A>]. For example: </P><PRE>     Files:
      c6f698f19f2a2aa07dbb9bbda90a2754 571925 example_1.2.orig.tar.gz
      938512f08422f3509ff36f125f5873ba 6220 example_1.2-1.diff.gz
</PRE>
<P>The exact forms of the filenames are described in <A=20
href=3D"http://www.debian.org/doc/debian-policy/ap-pkg-sourcepkg.html#s-p=
kg-sourcearchives">Source=20
packages as archives, Section C.3</A>. </P>
<P>In the <CODE>.changes</CODE> file this contains one line per file =
being=20
uploaded. Each line contains the MD5 checksum, size, section and =
priority and=20
the filename. For example: </P><PRE>     Files:
      4c31ab7bfc40d3cf49d7811987390357 1428 text extra example_1.2-1.dsc
      c6f698f19f2a2aa07dbb9bbda90a2754 571925 text extra =
example_1.2.orig.tar.gz
      938512f08422f3509ff36f125f5873ba 6220 text extra =
example_1.2-1.diff.gz
      7c98fe853b3bbb47a00e5cd129b6cb56 703542 text extra =
example_1.2-1_i386.deb
</PRE>
<P>The <A=20
href=3D"http://www.debian.org/doc/debian-policy/ch-controlfields.html#s-f=
-Section">section</A>=20
and <A=20
href=3D"http://www.debian.org/doc/debian-policy/ch-controlfields.html#s-f=
-Priority">priority</A>=20
are the values of the corresponding fields in the main source control =
file. If=20
no section or priority is specified then <SAMP>-</SAMP> should be used, =
though=20
section and priority values must be specified for new packages to be =
installed=20
properly. </P>
<P>The special value <SAMP>byhand</SAMP> for the section in a=20
<SAMP>.changes</SAMP> file indicates that the file in question is not an =

ordinary package file and must by installed by hand by the distribution=20
maintainers. If the section is <SAMP>byhand</SAMP> the priority should =
be=20
<SAMP>-</SAMP>. </P>
<P>If a new Debian revision of a package is being shipped and no new =
original=20
source archive is being distributed the <SAMP>.dsc</SAMP> must still =
contain the=20
<SAMP>Files</SAMP> field entry for the original source archive=20
<CODE><VAR>package</VAR>_<VAR>upstream-version</VAR>.orig.tar.gz</CODE>, =
but the=20
<CODE>.changes</CODE> file should leave it out. In this case the =
original source=20
archive on the distribution site must match exactly, byte-for-byte, the =
original=20
source archive which was used to generate the <CODE>.dsc</CODE> file and =
diff=20
which are being uploaded. </P>
<HR>

<H3><A name=3Ds-f-Closes></A>5.6.22 <SAMP>Closes</SAMP></H3>
<P>A space-separated list of bug report numbers that the upload governed =
by the=20
.changes file closes. </P>
<HR>

<H3><A name=3Ds-f-Homepage></A>5.6.23 <SAMP>Homepage</SAMP></H3>
<P>The URL of the web site for this package, preferably (when =
applicable) the=20
site from which the original source can be obtained and any additional =
upstream=20
documentation or information may be found. The content of this field is =
a simple=20
URL without any surrounding characters such as <SAMP>&lt;&gt;</SAMP>. =
</P>
<HR>

<H3><A name=3Ds-f-Checksums></A>5.6.24 <SAMP>Checksums-Sha1</SAMP> and=20
<SAMP>Checksums-Sha256</SAMP></H3>
<P>These multiline fields contain a list of files with a checksum and =
size for=20
each one. Both <SAMP>Checksums-Sha1</SAMP> and =
<SAMP>Checksums-Sha256</SAMP>=20
have the same syntax and differ only in the checksum algorithm used: =
SHA-1 for=20
<SAMP>Checksums-Sha1</SAMP> and SHA-256 for =
<SAMP>Checksums-Sha256</SAMP>. </P>
<P><SAMP>Checksums-Sha1</SAMP> and <SAMP>Checksums-Sha256</SAMP> are =
multiline=20
fields. The first line of the field value (the part on the same line as=20
<SAMP>Checksums-Sha1:</SAMP> or <SAMP>Checksums-Sha256:</SAMP>) is =
always empty.=20
The content of the field is expressed as continuation lines, one line =
per file.=20
Each line consists of the checksum, a space, the file size, a space, and =
the=20
file name. For example (from a <CODE>.changes</CODE> file): </P><PRE>    =
 Checksums-Sha1:
      1f418afaa01464e63cc1ee8a66a05f0848bd155c 1276 example_1.0-1.dsc
      a0ed1456fad61116f868b1855530dbe948e20f06 171602 =
example_1.0.orig.tar.gz
      5e86ecf0671e113b63388dac81dd8d00e00ef298 6137 =
example_1.0-1.debian.tar.gz
      71a0ff7da0faaf608481195f9cf30974b142c183 548402 =
example_1.0-1_i386.deb
     Checksums-Sha256:
      ac9d57254f7e835bed299926fd51bf6f534597cc3fcc52db01c4bffedae81272 =
1276 example_1.0-1.dsc
      0d123be7f51e61c4bf15e5c492b484054be7e90f3081608a5517007bfb1fd128 =
171602 example_1.0.orig.tar.gz
      f54ae966a5f580571ae7d9ef5e1df0bd42d63e27cb505b27957351a495bc6288 =
6137 example_1.0-1.debian.tar.gz
      3bec05c03974fdecd11d020fc2e8250de8404867a8a2ce865160c250eb723664 =
548402 example_1.0-1_i386.deb
</PRE>
<P>In the <CODE>.dsc</CODE> file, these fields should list all files =
that make=20
up the source package. In the <CODE>.changes</CODE> file, these fields =
should=20
list all files being uploaded. The list of files in these fields must =
match the=20
list of files in the <SAMP>Files</SAMP> field. </P>
<HR>

<H3><A name=3Ds-f-DM-Upload-Allowed></A>5.6.25 =
<SAMP>DM-Upload-Allowed</SAMP></H3>
<P>Indicates that Debian Maintainers may upload this package to the =
Debian=20
archive. The only valid value is <SAMP>yes</SAMP>. If the field=20
<SAMP>DM-Upload-Allowed: yes</SAMP> is present in the source section of =
the=20
source control file of the most recent version of a package in unstable =
or=20
experimental, the Debian archive will accept uploads of this package =
signed with=20
a key in the Debian Maintainer keyring. See the General Resolution =
<CODE><A=20
href=3D"http://www.debian.org/vote/2007/vote_003">Endorse the concept of =
Debian=20
Maintainers</A></CODE> for more details. </P>
<HR>

<H3><A name=3Ds-f-VCS-fields></A>5.6.26 Version Control System (VCS) =
fields</H3>
<P>Debian source packages are increasingly developed using VCSs. The =
purpose of=20
the following fields is to indicate a publicly accessible repository =
where the=20
Debian source package is developed. </P>
<DL>
  <DT><SAMP>Vcs-Browser</SAMP></DT>
  <DD>
  <P>URL of a web interface for browsing the repository. </P></DD></DL>
<DL>
  <DT><SAMP>Vcs-Arch</SAMP>, <SAMP>Vcs-Bzr</SAMP> (Bazaar),=20
  <SAMP>Vcs-Cvs</SAMP>, <SAMP>Vcs-Darcs</SAMP>, <SAMP>Vcs-Git</SAMP>,=20
  <SAMP>Vcs-Hg</SAMP> (Mercurial), <SAMP>Vcs-Mtn</SAMP> (Monotone),=20
  <SAMP>Vcs-Svn</SAMP> (Subversion)</DT>
  <DD>
  <P>The field name identifies the VCS. The field's value uses the =
version=20
  control system's conventional syntax for describing repository =
locations and=20
  should be sufficient to locate the repository used for packaging. =
Ideally, it=20
  also locates the branch used for development of new versions of the =
Debian=20
  package. </P>
  <P>In the case of Git, the value consists of a URL, optionally =
followed by the=20
  word <SAMP>-b</SAMP> and the name of a branch in the indicated =
repository,=20
  following the syntax of the <SAMP>git clone</SAMP> command. If no =
branch is=20
  specified, the packaging should be on the default branch. </P>
  <P>More than one different VCS may be specified for the same package.=20
</P></DD></DL>
<HR>

<H2><A name=3Ds5.7></A>5.7 User-defined fields</H2>
<P>Additional user-defined fields may be added to the source package =
control=20
file. Such fields will be ignored, and not copied to (for example) =
binary or=20
Debian source control files or upload control files. </P>
<P>If you wish to add additional unsupported fields to these output =
files you=20
should use the mechanism described here. </P>
<P>Fields in the main source control information file with names =
starting=20
<SAMP>X</SAMP>, followed by one or more of the letters <SAMP>BCS</SAMP> =
and a=20
hyphen <SAMP>-</SAMP>, will be copied to the output files. Only the part =
of the=20
field name after the hyphen will be used in the output file. Where the =
letter=20
<SAMP>B</SAMP> is used the field will appear in binary package control =
files,=20
where the letter <SAMP>S</SAMP> is used in Debian source control files =
and where=20
<SAMP>C</SAMP> is used in upload control (<SAMP>.changes</SAMP>) files. =
</P>
<P>For example, if the main source information control file contains the =
field=20
</P><PRE>       XBS-Comment: I stand between the candle and the star.
</PRE>
<P>then the binary and Debian source control files will contain the =
field </P><PRE>       Comment: I stand between the candle and the star.
</PRE>
<HR>

